II. Core Architecture Requirements
A. Data Layer
Storage Engine

 Embed a local-first database engine — CRDTs (Conflict-free Replicated Data Types) for all patient records, so offline edits always merge deterministically
 Candidate: CR-SQLite (SQLite with CRDT extensions) — runs on phone, server, browser
 All data encrypted at rest: AES-256-GCM with per-record keys
 Key management: device-local keystore (Android Keystore / iOS Secure Enclave) at T0; a local KMS (e.g., HashiCorp Vault in dev mode) at T1+
 FHIR R4 as canonical data model — every record is a FHIR resource internally, so interoperability is structural, not bolted on
 Immutable audit log (append-only, cryptographically chained — think a local blockchain-like ledger) for every record access, edit, and transmission event

Schema Design

 Patient identity as a deterministic UUID derived from demographic anchors (DOB + facility-assigned ID) — solves duplicate patient risk across offline nodes
 Every resource carries: created_by, created_at, modified_by, modified_at, origin_node_id, sync_vector_clock
 Soft deletes only — regulatory compliance requires record retention


B. Sync & Mesh Layer
This is the hardest part architecturally.
Peer Discovery

 mDNS / Bonjour for LAN peer discovery (zero-config, works on any LAN)
 Bluetooth Low Energy beaconing for sub-LAN scenarios (two phones in a clinic with no router)
 WiFi Direct as fallback for peer-to-peer data transfer
 Each node has a persistent node identity (Ed25519 keypair, generated at install) — this is how the mesh knows who is who regardless of IP

Sync Protocol

 Build on Automerge or Yjs (mature CRDT sync libraries) rather than rolling your own
 Sync is pull-based with push notifications — nodes advertise a vector clock; peers pull only the delta
 Conflict resolution rules must be domain-specific, not just "last write wins":

Medication records: flag conflict for human review, never auto-resolve
Administrative fields: last-write-wins acceptable
Vitals timeseries: merge by timestamp, duplicates deduplicated by hash


 Sync sessions are encrypted with ephemeral session keys (X25519 key exchange per session)
 Bandwidth-aware sync: detect available bandwidth, prioritize critical records (active admissions, current medications) over historical records

Conflict & Consistency

 Define per-resource-type consistency requirements (eventual vs. strong)
 Patient identity merging (two offline nodes created the same patient): fuzzy match on demographics, flag for admin review with a merge UI
 Sync state machine: local_only → pending_sync → synced → conflict → resolved


C. Security & Compliance
Authentication & Authorization

 Offline-capable auth: credentials stored as salted Argon2id hashes locally — no server dependency to log in
 TOTP 2FA optional at T0, required at T2+, with offline TOTP (RFC 6238 — works without internet)
 Role model: Patient, Clinician, Nurse, Admin, Researcher, Super-Admin
 Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC) rather than simple RBAC — allows rules like "Clinician can access records of patients assigned to their team within their department in the last 30 days"
 Department silos enforced at the data layer, not just the UI — a query from a cardiology user physically cannot return oncology-siloed records

Transport Security

 All sync over TLS 1.3 minimum when on internet; DTLS for local mesh
 Certificate pinning for known institutional servers
 mTLS (mutual TLS) between hospital nodes — both sides authenticate

Regulatory Alignment (design for the hardest applicable standard)

 HIPAA (US) — baseline for any deployment serving global research partners
 DISHA / IT Act (India) — relevant for your primary market
 GDPR (EU) — for T4 research federation
 Design to HL7 FHIR R4 compliance from day one
 Audit log must be tamper-evident, exportable, and retained per jurisdiction rules
 Right to access / right to erasure: implement a patient data export (FHIR Bundle) and a "legal hold" flag before any delete


III. AI / Local Intelligence Layer
This is the differentiator — local models that work offline.
Input Processing Pipeline
Handwritten Records (OCR)

 On-device: TrOCR (Microsoft, MIT licensed) — transformer-based, handles messy handwriting well; quantized to run on mobile
 Fallback pipeline: image → preprocessing (deskew, denoise via OpenCV) → OCR → structured extraction
 Output always goes to a human review queue — never auto-committed to patient record
 Language support prioritization: English, Hindi, regional scripts (Devanagari) — use script detection before routing to the right model

PDF Ingestion

 pdfplumber / pypdf for text-layer PDFs
 For scanned PDFs: rasterize pages → same OCR pipeline as above
 Lab report parser: regex + ML hybrid to extract structured values (test name, result, unit, reference range) → map to FHIR Observation resources
 Discharge summary parser: NLP entity extraction → map to FHIR Composition

Voice & Dictation

 On-device STT: Whisper (OpenAI, MIT license) — specifically whisper.cpp for mobile/embedded deployment; tiny or base model for T0, medium for T1+
 In-app dictation: streaming audio → whisper.cpp → live transcript → structured SOAP note extraction
 Voice commands: intent classifier (lightweight, distilBERT-based) for navigation and quick-entry commands
 Speaker diarization at T2+ (multiple speakers in a ward round recording)

