Security Architecture: Yes, You Need a Dedicated Protocol Layer
This is the most important architectural decision after the CRDT choice. The answer is: ABAC and encryption are related but separate concerns, and conflating them will hurt you.
Think of it as three distinct systems that compose:
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│           WHAT YOU'RE ALLOWED TO DO              │  ← ABAC (Policy Engine)
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│           WHETHER YOU ARE WHO YOU SAY            │  ← Identity & Auth
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│           WHETHER THE DATA IS PROTECTED          │  ← Cryptographic Layer
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
Layer 1: The Cryptographic Layer (Innermost, Always On)
This lives entirely in the Rust core. It is not access control — it is the physical protection of data regardless of who is asking.
Key Hierarchy:
Device Master Key (DMK)
│  derived from: hardware keystore + user passphrase (Argon2id)
│  never leaves the device
│
├── Patient Record Key (PRK) — one per patient
│   encrypted with DMK, stored alongside record
│   decrypted only when a session is active
│
├── Sync Session Key (SSK) — ephemeral, per sync session
│   X25519 key exchange between two node identities
│   forward secrecy: past sessions can't be decrypted even if
│   node key is later compromised
│
└── Audit Log Key (ALK) — append-only signing key
    signs each audit entry (Ed25519)
    cannot be used to decrypt anything
Construction:

Use libsodium (via the Rust sodiumoxide or dryoc crates) — it is the most widely audited cryptographic library available, with a high-level API that prevents misuse
Never implement your own primitives. Libsodium's crypto_secretstream for streaming encryption, crypto_box for sealed records, crypto_sign for audit entries
PRKs are what make the system truly zero-knowledge at the storage level — even if someone extracts the SQLite file from the device, individual records are encrypted with separate keys

On-Device Key Storage:

Android: Android Keystore System (hardware-backed on most devices made after 2017)
iOS: Secure Enclave (hardware-backed)
Linux/Pi: TPM 2.0 if available; fallback to a key file protected by OS permissions + passphrase

Layer 2: Identity & Authentication
This establishes who the session belongs to before any access decision is made.
Node Identity (permanent):
Every installed instance of New Loka generates an Ed25519 keypair at first run. This is the node's identity on the mesh. It is:

Stored in the hardware keystore
Used to sign all data originating from this node
The basis for trust establishment when joining a clinic/hospital network

User Identity (session):

Credentials: username + passphrase, hashed with Argon2id, stored locally
On login: derive a session token (HMAC-SHA256 of user identity + timestamp + node identity)
Session token is short-lived (configurable: 4h default, 15min for high-security deployments)
Offline TOTP (RFC 6238) for 2FA — works without any server

Trust Establishment Between Nodes (the hard problem):
When a new node wants to join a clinic mesh, you need a trust ceremony:
New Node                          Admin Node
    │                                  │
    │── broadcasts node_id + pub_key ──│
    │                                  │  Admin reviews, approves in UI
    │←─ signed trust certificate ──────│
    │                                  │
    │  (stores cert, now trusted by    │
    │   all nodes that trust Admin)    │
This is essentially a lightweight PKI — the first admin at a deployment is the root of trust, and they sign trust certificates for new nodes. At T3, this integrates with the institution's existing certificate authority.
Layer 3: ABAC Policy Engine
This sits above the crypto and identity layers. It answers: given a verified identity and a decrypted resource, is this action permitted?
Policy Structure:
Policy := Subject × Resource × Action × Context → Permit | Deny | Not_Applicable

Subject:    { user_id, roles[], department_id, node_id }
Resource:   { patient_id, record_type, owning_department, sensitivity_level }
Action:     { read | write | delete | export | share | print }
Context:    { time_of_day, is_emergency_override, patient_assigned_to_subject,
              days_since_last_encounter, sync_state }
Key policies to implement:
PERMIT  Clinician READ Patient.record
        WHERE Patient.assigned_team CONTAINS Clinician.team_id
        AND record.department_id = Clinician.department_id

PERMIT  Clinician READ Patient.record
        WHERE Context.is_emergency_override = true
        AND Action logged with override_reason (audit required)

DENY    ANY READ Patient.record
        WHERE record.department_id ≠ Subject.department_id
        AND Subject.role ≠ {Admin, Super-Admin}
        AND Context.is_emergency_override = false

PERMIT  Nurse WRITE Patient.vitals
        WHERE Patient.assigned_ward = Nurse.assigned_ward

DENY    Nurse DELETE ANY

PERMIT  Admin READ audit_log
        WHERE audit_log.department_id = Admin.department_id
Emergency Override ("Break Glass"):
This is a regulatory requirement — a clinician must always be able to access a record in an emergency, even across department silos. Implement it as:

Explicit UI action: "Access Emergency Record" with mandatory reason entry
Immediately logged to immutable audit trail
Generates an alert to the owning department's admin
Time-limited access (e.g., 2 hours)

How ABAC Relates to Crypto:
Request arrives
      │
      ▼
Identity verified? (Layer 2)
      │ No → Reject (never touch encrypted data)
      │ Yes
      ▼
ABAC policy check (Layer 3)
      │ Deny → Reject (never touch encrypted data)
      │ Permit
      ▼
Decrypt PRK with DMK (Layer 1)
      │
      ▼
Decrypt record, serve to session
      │
      ▼
Re-encrypt before write, log to audit trail
The critical property: the cryptographic layer cannot be bypassed by policy misconfiguration. Even if an ABAC rule is wrong, the encrypted record is useless without the PRK, and the PRK is only unwrapped inside a verified session. ABAC and crypto are defense in depth — each is a complete barrier independently.
How This Extends Across the Network
When data moves between nodes (sync), the same stack applies but in transport mode:
Sending Node                          Receiving Node
      │                                     │
      │  1. ABAC: am I permitted to          │
      │     share this record to that node? │
      │  2. Establish SSK via X25519        │
      │  3. Re-encrypt record envelope      │
      │     with SSK (not PRK)              │
      │─── encrypted sync payload ─────────→│
      │                                     │  4. Verify sender node cert
      │                                     │  5. Decrypt with SSK
      │                                     │  6. ABAC: am I permitted to
      │                                     │     receive and store this?
      │                                     │  7. Re-encrypt with local PRK
      │                                     │  8. Store, log receipt
The record is never in plaintext in transit, and the receiving node's ABAC independently validates the transfer — so a compromised sending node cannot force unauthorized records onto a receiving node.

