HL7 Certification: Do You Need It?
Short answer: you need it to sell to institutions, not to build or deploy.
What HL7 Certification Actually Is
HL7 International doesn't certify software directly for FHIR. What exists is a layered ecosystem:
BodyWhat They DoMandatory?HL7 InternationalMaintains the FHIR standard itself. No product certification program.N/AONC (US)Certifies Health IT for US federal programs (Medicare/Medicaid reimbursement). Requires FHIR R4 as of 2023.Only if billing US federal programsInfoway (Canada)Similar national certification bodyOnly for Canadian public health programsIHE (Integrating the Healthcare Enterprise)Publishes integration profiles (IHE profiles sit on top of FHIR). Connectathon testing available.Voluntary, but expected by large hospitalsNABH / NHA (India)National Accreditation Board for Hospitals. Abdm (Ayushman Bharat Digital Mission) mandates FHIR R4 for any system connecting to the national health stack.If integrating with ABHA/NHA ecosystem
What This Means for New Loka
Mandatory for your primary market (India):
If any deployment connects to the ABHA (Ayushman Bharat Health Account) national stack — which any serious hospital deployment eventually will — you must comply with NHA's FHIR implementation guide. This is not optional certification so much as a conformance requirement for API access. NHA publishes their own FHIR profiles (constraints on top of base FHIR R4).
Practically mandatory for T3 hospital sales:
Large hospitals will ask for IHE profile conformance. Specifically:

IHE PDQm — Patient Demographics Query for Mobile
IHE MHD — Mobile access to Health Documents
IHE PIXm — Patient Identifier Cross-referencing for Mobile

These are exactly what New Loka is doing anyway. You're not building extra features — you're documenting and testing that your existing implementation conforms.
Not mandatory for T0/T1:
A single doctor using New Loka on their phone has no certification obligation whatsoever. They're not billing a national program, not connecting to a hospital network, not exchanging records with another institution.
The Practical Path
Phase 1 (T0/T1 launch):
  Build to FHIR R4 spec internally.
  No certification needed.
  Self-declare FHIR R4 conformance.

Phase 2 (T3 hospital sales):
  Publish a Capability Statement (FHIR resource that declares 
  exactly what your server supports — mandatory for any 
  FHIR server, free to produce).
  Run your implementation through the official 
  FHIR validator (free tool from HL7).
  Participate in an IHE Connectathon 
  (annual events, open registration, not expensive).

Phase 3 (India national integration):
  Register with NHA sandbox.
  Implement ABDM FHIR profiles.
  Complete NHA's integration testing process.
  This unlocks ABHA linkage — significant market differentiator.
The Capability Statement is worth understanding — it's a FHIR resource your server exposes at [base]/metadata that declares every resource type you support, every operation, every search parameter. It's how other systems know what they can ask of you. You generate it once and keep it updated.

FHIR in the Single Doctor Setup
This is a genuinely interesting design problem. The naive answer — "just run a lightweight FHIR server on the phone" — is wrong. Here's why, and what to do instead.
The Problem With a Phone-Based FHIR Server
A real FHIR server (HAPI FHIR, Medplum) is a Java or Node application with a relational database backend. Running that on a phone means:

200–400MB RAM consumed constantly
Battery drain from a persistent HTTP server
Android and iOS actively kill background servers
Completely unnecessary for a single user with no external queries

A single doctor is not exchanging FHIR resources with anyone. There is no interoperability requirement at T0 — yet.
The Right Mental Model: FHIR as Internal Schema, Not Protocol
At T0, FHIR is your data model, not your transport protocol. The distinction is critical:
What FHIR gives you at T0:
  ✓ A well-defined, clinically validated schema for every 
    data type you'll ever store
  ✓ Coded terminologies (SNOMED, LOINC, ICD-10) baked in
  ✓ A path to interoperability the moment the doctor 
    wants to share a record or move to a bigger system
  ✓ Regulatory defensibility ("we use the international 
    standard for health data")

What FHIR does NOT require at T0:
  ✗ A running HTTP server
  ✗ REST API endpoints
  ✗ Any network at all
  ✗ Certification of any kind
How It Actually Works at T0
FHIR resources live as serialized JSON objects 
inside CR-SQLite, encrypted with PRK.

cr-sqlite schema (simplified):

  TABLE fhir_resources (
    id          TEXT PRIMARY KEY,  -- "Patient/pat-7f3a9c"
    resource_type TEXT,             -- "Patient"
    content     BLOB,               -- AES-GCM encrypted JSON
    vector_clock TEXT,              -- CRDT metadata
    created_at  INTEGER,
    modified_at INTEGER
  )

The Rust core speaks FHIR internally.
The Flutter UI speaks to the Rust core.
No HTTP. No server. No ports open.

When Dr. Kulkarni enters a patient's vitals:
  UI → Rust Core → FHIR Observation JSON 
  → encrypted → stored in SQLite
  Nothing else happens.
What the Single Doctor Actually Gets
The value proposition at T0 has nothing to do with interoperability and everything to do with:
Replacing the paper register / WhatsApp note:

Structured patient list, searchable
Timeline of every visit, every prescription, every lab
Voice dictation → structured note in seconds
Photo of a handwritten referral → parsed into the record
Drug interaction checking against their own prescription history

The "beat a phone call" test at T0:
A solo doctor wants to know what they prescribed a patient six months ago. Currently: scroll through WhatsApp, search a paper register, or call the patient. In New Loka: patient name → search → medication history → 3 seconds.
When Interoperability Wakes Up
The FHIR-as-internal-schema choice pays off the moment the doctor needs to do any of these:
Share a referral letter:
Dr. Kulkarni refers a patient to a cardiologist.
  
  New Loka generates FHIR Bundle (referral type):
    Patient + Condition + Medications + relevant Observations
  
  Export options:
    → PDF (rendered from FHIR, human-readable)
      for doctors who don't use New Loka
    → QR code containing encrypted FHIR Bundle
      for doctors who do use New Loka
      (receiving doctor scans → imports directly into their T0 instance)
    → ABHA-linked share (if both parties have ABHA IDs)
      → NHA-compliant FHIR exchange
  
  The cardiologist never needs to know FHIR exists.
  The data is structured underneath.
Patient moves to a hospital:
Patient is admitted to a T3 hospital.
Dr. Kulkarni shares their record.

  New Loka exports: FHIR Bundle (complete patient history)
  Hospital's EMR imports it natively (if FHIR R4 compliant)
  Or: New Loka's own hospital instance ingests it directly
  
